Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Spanish: variant of   Muriel  , a habitational name from any of the places so named, from the Latin personal name <i>Maurellus</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Muriel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Fernando, Alfredo, Angel, Francisco, Javier, Juan, Alejo, Amador, Candido, Diego.","Spanish: habitational name from any of the places called Muriel, in Soria, Gaudalajara, or Valladolid.","English (mainly East Anglia): variant of   Murrell  ."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Einudd ap Morien was born about 1020, in Denbighshire, Wales, his father, Morien Ap Morgeneu, was 27 and his mother, Gwenllian verch Rhys of Dyffryn Clwyd, was 24. He married Efa ferch Llywelyn about 1054, in Dyffryn, Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died about 1094, in Montgomeryshire, Wales, at the age of 76."},"et":{"about 1020–about 1094":"umbes 1020–umbes 1094","1020–1094":"1020–1094","1024–1119":"1024–1119","1055–1134":"1055–1134","1060–Male":"1060–Surnud","1063–1132":"1063–1132","0994–1094":"0994–1094","0998–1020":"0998–1020","about 1094":"umbes 1094","about 1060":"umbes 1060","about 1063":"umbes 1063","1055":"1055","1132":"1132","1020":"1020","1030":"1030","1063":"1063","1094":"1094","1060":"1060","0994":"0994","1134":"1134","1024":"1024","about 1054":"umbes 1054","from 1065 to 1119":"1065 kuni 1119","about 1020":"umbes 1020","0998":"0998","1119":"1119","Dyffryn Clwyd, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Dyffryn, Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom":"Dyffryn, Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom","Dyffryn Clwyd, Gwynedd, Wales":"Dyffryn, Gwynedd, Wales, United Kingdom","Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales","Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1020–about 1094":"noin 1020–noin 1094","1020–1094":"1020–1094","1024–1119":"1024–1119","1055–1134":"1055–1134","1060–Male":"1060–Kuollut","